{"parentUuid":"bd1e46e6-07be-45f8-ab6d-ef7686b18d52","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a18902932a394df42","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_011Ccw9BArTZgH2MtLpU9ey9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01LGEbG1zy6QnFuftL5npXVF","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/mnt/c/Users/brett/OneDrive/Documents/GitHub/meterly-pipeline-test/docs/system_architecture.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1598,"cache_read_input_tokens":48523,"output_tokens":193,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1598},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":193,"cache_read_input_tokens":48523,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1598,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1598,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccw9B8wrupJejeaLksLe2","attributionAgent":"documentation","type":"assistant","uuid":"65554e78-8fd3-4ce4-aa8a-1ae3f02406c4","timestamp":"2026-07-11T23:31:22.688Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/mnt/c/Users/brett/OneDrive/Documents/GitHub/meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"8b12bd3f-3c00-43c5-ad29-92ed49e714d3","version":"2.1.207","gitBranch":"feature/usage-daily"}
{"parentUuid":"65554e78-8fd3-4ce4-aa8a-1ae3f02406c4","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"bab18d11-a54d-4359-a1e4-66e491360a7c","agentId":"a18902932a394df42","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LGEbG1zy6QnFuftL5npXVF","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Meterly — system architecture\n2\t\n3\t## Overview\n4\t\n5\tMeterly ingests metered usage events, serves aggregated per-customer/metric\n6\tcounters (single-bucket read or a streamed CSV export), and enforces\n7\tadmin-set per-customer, per-metric usage caps (\"quotas\"), which an admin key\n8\tcan also list and remove. Six authenticated HTTP endpoints, one PostgreSQL\n9\tdatabase, one Redis rate-limit store, running as a Docker container on ECS\n10\tFargate behind an ALB.\n11\t\n12\t```\n13\tClient --HTTPS+API key--> ALB --> FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\n14\t                                     |-- Tier-1 (IP) / Tier-2 (api_key_id) throttle --> Redis\n15\t                                     |-- bound-parameter SQL, RLS-scoped -------------> RDS PostgreSQL\n16\t                                     |-- DB credential fetch ------------------------> Secrets Manager\n17\t                                     |-- traces/logs/errors -------------------------> CloudWatch/X-Ray/Sentry\n18\t```\n19\t\n20\t```mermaid\n21\tflowchart LR\n22\t    Client[Client] -->|\"HTTPS + API key\"| ALB[ALB]\n23\t    ALB --> FastAPI[\"FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\"]\n24\t    FastAPI -->|\"Tier-1 IP+route / Tier-2 api_key_id throttle\"| Redis[(Redis)]\n25\t    FastAPI -->|\"require_api_key: cache hit or Argon2id verify\"| AuthDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: api_keys)]\n26\t    FastAPI -->|\"POST /v1/events: insert + quota check + rollup upsert\"| EventsDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: events / usage_rollup / quotas)]\n27\t    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/usage: read rollup\"| EventsDB\n28\t    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/usage/export: pre-flight COUNT + streamed SELECT\"| EventsDB\n29\t    FastAPI -->|\"PUT /v1/quotas: upsert cap\"| EventsDB\n30\t    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/quotas: list caller's caps\"| EventsDB\n31\t    FastAPI -->|\"DELETE /v1/quotas: remove one cap\"| EventsDB\n32\t    FastAPI -->|\"DB credential fetch\"| Secrets[Secrets Manager]\n33\t    FastAPI -->|\"traces/logs/errors\"| Observability[\"CloudWatch / X-Ray / Sentry\"]\n34\t```\n35\t\n36\t## Request flow — `POST /v1/events`\n37\t\n38\t1. Request-id/trace assigned, security headers queued (`src/logging/middleware.py`, `src/api/middleware.py`).\n39\t2. Tier-1 IP+route throttle (Redis token bucket; fails open on a Redis outage).\n40\t3. `require_api_key` — split-token parse, in-process verification-cache check,\n41\t   falling back to a DB lookup + Argon2id verify on a cache miss\n42\t   (`src/auth/__init__.py`, `src/auth/api_key.py`).\n43\t4. Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`).\n44\t5. Pydantic schema validation (`src/api/schemas/events.py`) — anchored\n45\t   allowlists, `extra='forbid'`.\n46\t6. `events_service.create_event` — one transaction:\n47\t   `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING`, and only\n48\t   if a row was inserted:\n49\t   - the quota check: `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` locks the caller's\n50\t     quota row for `(customer, metric)` (if one exists) and reads the\n51\t     current-window rollup total fresh; if `R + Q > L` the service raises\n52\t     `QuotaExceededError` (429 `quota_exceeded`, `Retry-After` to the next\n53\t     hour boundary), which propagates out of the transaction and rolls back\n54\t     the event insert — no partial write, no rollup increment\n55\t     (`src/services/events_service.py`, `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n56\t   - otherwise, `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO UPDATE` the `usage_rollup`\n57\t     counter (`src/repositories/events_repo.py`).\n58\t   A duplicate `idempotency_key` (replay) never reaches the quota check at\n59\t   all — only the winning-insert branch does.\n60\t7. Error-envelope boundary catches anything unhandled and returns the generic\n61\t   `{error:{code,message,requestId}}` shape (`src/api/errors.py`); `AppError`\n62\t   lets a handler attach an explicit `app_code` (e.g. `quota_exceeded`) that\n63\t   overrides the default status->code map, so two different 429s\n64\t   (`rate_limited` vs. `quota_exceeded`) stay distinguishable to the caller.\n65\t\n66\t## Request flow — `GET /v1/usage`\n67\t\n68\tSame auth/throttle/error stack; the service floors `window` to the UTC hour\n69\tand reads a single `usage_rollup` row scoped by the caller's `api_key_id`\n70\t(`src/services/usage_service.py`, `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`). A missing\n71\tbucket returns zeros with 200, never 404.\n72\t\n73\t## Request flow — `GET /v1/usage/export`\n74\t\n75\tSame auth/throttle/error stack, plus a two-phase pre-flight-then-stream\n76\tdesign (`src/api/routes/usage_export.py`,\n77\t`src/services/usage_export_service.py`,\n78\t`src/repositories/usage_repo.py`):\n79\t\n80\t1. `UsageExportQueryParams` validates the optional `customer_id`/`metric`/\n81\t   `from`/`to` filters (`src/api/schemas/usage_export.py`) — reuses the same\n82\t   `CustomerId`/`Metric` anchored allowlists as `events.py` and the same\n83\t   `[now-90d, now+1h]` bound idiom as `usage.py`'s `window`, applied here to\n84\t   a `[from, to]` range.\n85\t2. **Pre-flight cap check** (`prepare_export`): a `COUNT(*)` over the\n86\t   caller's rows (scoped by `api_key_id` first, plus the optional filters)\n87\t   inside its own transaction. Over 100,000 rows -> 422\n88\t   `validation_failed`, logged at `warn` (`usage.export.rejected`). This\n89\t   runs, and fully resolves, *before* any response byte — once a\n90\t   `StreamingResponse` is constructed the status line is already 200 and the\n91\t   cap decision can no longer cleanly 422. Any *other* (non-cap) error here\n92\t   propagates uncaught to the error-envelope boundary: a fail-closed generic\n93\t   500, transaction rolled back, no stream ever started.\n94\t3. **Stream** (`stream_export_csv`): a `StreamingResponse` whose body\n95\t   generator is pulled by Starlette only after the handler returns, so it\n96\t   opens its **own** tenant-scoped transaction (the `SET LOCAL\n97\t   app.current_api_key_id` RLS-backstop setting and the server-side cursor\n98\t   both need to stay valid for the whole stream, not just the pre-flight\n99\t   phase). Yields the header row first, always (an empty result is a 200\n100\t   header-only CSV, never 404), then one CSV-encoded row per record from\n101\t   `stream_usage_rollups` (`ORDER BY window_start, customer_id, metric` — a\n102\t   fixed literal, never client-derived — `LIMIT 100000`), each row written\n103\t   into a reused `io.StringIO` via stdlib `csv.writer` (RFC 4180, CRLF,\n104\t   `QUOTE_MINIMAL`) and drained to bytes immediately — constant memory\n105\t   throughout. `customer_id`/`metric` text cells pass through\n106\t   `src/api/csv_export.py`'s `escape_csv_text_cell` (the OWASP\n107\t   formula-injection defense: a leading `= + - @ \\t \\r` gets a `'` prefix)\n108\t   *before* reaching the writer; numeric/timestamp cells are formatted but\n109\t   never escaped (they're server-generated, never attacker-controlled).\n110\t   Logs exactly one `usage.export` audit event in a `finally` block\n111\t   (`rowCount`, `capped`, `completed`, filter-presence booleans — never the\n112\t   raw `customer_id`/`metric` values), so a client disconnect or a mid-stream\n113\t   DB error still records what was actually sent.\n114\t\n115\tResponse headers: `Content-Type: text/csv; charset=utf-8`,\n116\t`Content-Disposition: attachment; filename=\"usage-export-<UTC\n117\ttimestamp>.csv\"` (no tenant identifier in the filename), plus the inherited\n118\t`nosniff` and (via the existing `/v1/usage`-prefix rule in\n119\t`src/api/middleware.py`) `Cache-Control: no-store`.\n120\t\n121\t**Accepted risk — mid-stream failure truncates the CSV.** Once the 200\n122\tstatus line and header bytes are on the wire, an unhandled error partway\n123\tthrough the stream can no longer be converted to a clean error envelope; the\n124\tclient sees a truncated download it can re-request. This is strictly the\n125\t*post-200* case — the pre-flight `COUNT` phase above is fully recoverable\n126\tand does return the generic 500 envelope. Bounded by the row cap + Tier-2\n127\tthrottle + connection-pool sizing; batched keyset pagination is the future\n128\tmitigation if this needs closing further.\n129\t\n130\t## Request flow — `PUT /v1/quotas`\n131\t\n132\tAdmin-scoped create-or-replace of a per-customer, per-metric usage cap.\n133\tAuth -> Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle -> an `admin`-scope assertion in the\n134\troute's composed dependency (403 `forbidden` for a non-admin key) -> schema\n135\tvalidation (`src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) -> `upsert_tenant_quota`, a single\n136\t`INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ...\n137\tRETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted` that reports create-vs-replace in one\n138\tround-trip (201 create / 200 replace), with a `quota.upsert` audit log\n139\t(`src/api/routes/quotas.py`, `src/services/quota_service.py`,\n140\t`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n141\t\n142\t## Request flow — `GET /v1/quotas` and `DELETE /v1/quotas`\n143\t\n144\tBoth reuse the same `_require_admin_and_throttled` dependency chain as `PUT`\n145\t(auth -> Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle -> `admin`-scope assertion, 403\n146\t`forbidden` for a non-admin key) — no new auth path or scope\n147\t(`src/api/routes/quotas.py`).\n148\t\n149\t- **`GET /v1/quotas`** (`list_quotas_endpoint` -> `quota_service.list_tenant_quotas`\n150\t  -> `quotas_repo.list_quotas`) takes no request parameter and returns the\n151\t  caller's **full, unpaginated** quota list as `list[QuotaResponse]`\n152\t  (`{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` only), via an `api_key_id`-scoped\n153\t  `SELECT ... ORDER BY customer_id, metric` (index-friendly on the table's PK\n154\t  prefix, so the sort is effectively free). An empty tenant gets `200 []`,\n155\t  never 404. Deliberately not given a dedicated business-audit log (a plain\n156\t  read of the caller's own config, mirroring `GET /v1/usage`).\n157\t- **`DELETE /v1/quotas?customer_id=X&metric=Y`** (`delete_quota_endpoint` ->\n158\t  `quota_service.delete_tenant_quota` -> `quotas_repo.delete_quota`) validates\n159\t  the two query params through `QuotaDeleteParams` (the same anchored\n160\t  `CustomerId`/`Metric` allowlists `PUT` uses, `extra='forbid'`), then issues a\n161\t  single parameterized `DELETE ... WHERE api_key_id = :api_key_id AND\n162\t  customer_id = :customer_id AND metric = :metric RETURNING customer_id`. A\n163\t  matched row -> **204 No Content**; no matched row -> **404** `not_found`\n164\t  (explicit, not silently idempotent) — a cross-tenant delete attempt is\n165\t  indistinguishable from this outcome, since the `api_key_id` filter plus the\n166\t  `quotas_tenant_isolation` **FORCE** RLS backstop (migration `0003`) mean the\n167\t  query can never see another tenant's row to remove it. On success, logs one\n168\t  `quota.delete` INFO event (`userId`, `action=\"delete\"`, `customer_id`\n169\t  [facade-redacted], `metric`, `requestId`) — the audit trail for who removed\n170\t  which cap.\n171\t- **No `usage_rollup` side effect:** `delete_quota` issues **only** a `DELETE`\n172\t  on `quotas`; it never touches `usage_rollup`. A DELETE racing an in-flight\n173\t  `POST /v1/events` for the same `(customer, metric)` serializes on the shared\n174\t  quota-row lock (the DELETE's implicit row lock vs. the ingest's `SELECT ...\n175\t  FOR UPDATE OF q`) — whichever commits first determines the outcome for\n176\t  everything that reads after; no additional synchronization is added (the\n177\t  same replacement-race semantics `PUT` already has).\n178\t- **Safe-error / fail-closed:** an unexpected exception on either path (e.g. a\n179\t  DB driver/connection error) propagates to the existing\n180\t  `handle_unexpected_error` catch-all (`src/api/errors.py`) -> generic `{code:\n181\t  internal}` 500 (no stack/SQL/type/path leak). Because both service functions\n182\t  run inside `scoped_transaction`, the exception also rolls the transaction\n183\t  back — `DELETE` leaves the target row intact (no partial delete); `GET` is\n184\t  read-only, so there is nothing to unwind. Same boundary and guarantee as\n185\t  `POST /v1/events`'s precedent.\n186\t- **CORS:** `DELETE` was added to `configure_cors`'s `allow_methods`\n187\t  (`src/api/middleware.py`) for completeness — the origin allowlist is empty\n188\t  in this server-to-server API, so the change is not a live control.\n189\t\n190\t## Data model\n191\t\n192\t- `api_keys` — the tenant/credential table (migration 0001), extended with a\n193\t  `scope` column (migration 0003: `'ingest'` default, `'admin'` elevated).\n194\t  `secret_hash` is Argon2id; `key_id` is the public split-token lookup\n195\t  handle. `scope='admin'` is a superset scope — an admin key does everything\n196\t  an ingest key does, plus call `PUT`/`GET`/`DELETE /v1/quotas`; a tenant that\n197\t  wants quotas provisions one admin-scoped key and uses it for all three.\n198\t- `events` — append-only ingest log (migration 0001). `UNIQUE (api_key_id,\n199\t  idempotency_key)` is the idempotency guarantee; RLS policy\n200\t  `events_tenant_isolation` is the application-scoping backstop.\n201\t- `usage_rollup` — derived hourly aggregate (migration 0002, expand +\n202\t  backfill from `events`). Composite PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric,\n203\t  window_start)`; RLS policy `usage_rollup_tenant_isolation`.\n204\t- `quotas` — per-tenant, per-customer, per-metric usage caps (migration\n205\t  0003). PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`; `CHECK (limit_per_window >=\n206\t  1)`; RLS policy `quotas_tenant_isolation`. The `POST /v1/events` quota\n207\t  check takes `FOR UPDATE` on this row to serialize concurrent writers for\n208\t  the same `(customer, metric)` — see *Quota enforcement / atomicity* below.\n209\t\n210\t## Quota enforcement / atomicity\n211\t\n212\tStrict enforcement (\"usage can never exceed `L`\") is a check-then-act on a\n213\tshared counter — the classic TOCTOU. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked`\n214\t(`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`) makes it race-free with a `SELECT\n215\tlimit_per_window ... FOR UPDATE` on the quota row, run **as a separate\n216\tstatement from the subsequent `usage_rollup` read**, both inside the same\n217\ttransaction as the event insert and rollup increment\n218\t(`src/services/events_service.py`).\n219\t\n220\tThis two-round-trip shape is deliberate, not incidental: PostgreSQL's `FOR\n221\tUPDATE` only guarantees a fresh re-check of the *locked* row itself when a\n222\twaiter unblocks after the lock holder commits — it does **not** force a\n223\tfresh snapshot for another table read in the same statement (e.g. a `LEFT\n224\tJOIN` to `usage_rollup`). A waiter queued before the holder committed would\n225\tevaluate that join against its own pre-wait snapshot and read a stale total,\n226\tsilently letting concurrent writers jointly exceed the cap. Splitting the\n227\tlock-acquire and the rollup-read into two statements gives the second query\n228\tits own fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot (taken *after* the lock is held),\n229\twhich does reflect everything the previous holder just committed. This was\n230\tverified empirically during implementation: a single combined\n231\t`LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` statement let every concurrent waiter read\n232\tthe same stale total and all get admitted; the two-statement version\n233\tcorrectly serializes and caps admission at `L`\n234\t(`tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py`).\n235\t\n236\tUnlimited customers (no quota row) take no lock at all — the first `SELECT\n237\t... FOR UPDATE` simply matches zero rows, so the common, zero-contention\n238\tpath stays cheap (AC20 measures its added latency under load).\n239\t\n240\t## Auth\n241\t\n242\tSplit-token API keys (`mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>`), Argon2id-hashed at rest.\n243\tClients present the key in the standard bearer scheme —\n244\t`Authorization: Bearer mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` — which is also the auth\n245\tcontext a DAST job (ZAP/Schemathesis) reads to authenticate its scan (DAST-3).\n246\tAn in-process, TTL-bounded verification cache (keyed on the public `key_id`,\n247\tguarded by a constant-time digest comparison) avoids paying the Argon2id cost\n248\ton every request while the durable store stays Argon2id-only. See\n249\t`src/auth/__init__.py` for the full tradeoff writeup and\n250\t`scripts/seed_api_key.py` for the only key-provisioning path (no HTTP\n251\tendpoint in this build's scope; pass `--admin` to provision a `scope='admin'`\n252\tkey for `PUT`/`GET`/`DELETE /v1/quotas`, including the DAST-context admin test\n253\tkey, DAST-3).\n254\t\n255\t## Rate limiting\n256\t\n257\tTwo Redis token-bucket tiers (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`): Tier-1 pre-auth,\n258\tkeyed on IP+route; Tier-2 post-auth, keyed on the authenticated\n259\t`api_key_id`. Both fail open (log a warning, allow the request) on a Redis\n260\tconnection error rather than failing every request — an availability\n261\ttradeoff recorded in `.pipeline/surface-delta.md`.\n262\t\n263\t## Observability\n264\t\n265\tStructured JSON logs (structlog) to stdout -> CloudWatch, with a centralized\n266\tredaction processor (`src/logging/__init__.py`). OTel traces -> ADOT sidecar\n267\t-> X-Ray; Sentry for release-tagged error tracking with a `before_send`\n268\tPII/secret scrubber (`src/observability/`). SLO burn-rate alarms and the\n269\tminimum-three canary alarms are declared in `infra/modules/observability`.\n270\t\n271\t## Infrastructure\n272\t\n273\tTerraform under `infra/`: `modules/{network,compute,data,observability,edge}`\n274\thold the real resources; `envs/{staging,prod}/main.tf` are the two\n275\tself-contained deploy roots (own provider + backend, since Terraform only\n276\tpermits a backend configuration in a root module) that instantiate the same\n277\tmodules at different scale. See each module's file header comments for the\n278\tspecific resources and the security-baseline items they satisfy\n279\t(encryption at rest, private subnets, least-privilege IAM, no `BYPASSRLS`).\n280\t\n281\t## Known deviations / accepted risks\n282\t\n283\tSee `.pipeline/surface-delta.md` for the rate-limit fail-open behavior and the\n284\tOTel/Sentry wiring-at-construction-time change vs. the plan's original\n285\tlifespan-hook placement. See `plan.md`'s \"Open questions\" section for the\n286\taccepted risks around key-revocation latency, `api_key_id`-as-tenant-scope,\n287\tand the Postgres app-role bootstrap's CI-network-reachability prerequisite.\n288\t\n289\t**`GET /v1/usage/export` p95 at the 100,000-row cap — resolved (was: plan\n290\t§\"Open questions\" #1, originally unconfirmed).** The first measured p95\n291\t(~10.7s locally / 25.2s on testing's independent re-measure) was root-caused\n292\tduring debugging to the streaming generator yielding **one chunk per row**:\n293\tthe app's four nested `BaseHTTPMiddleware` layers (`src/main.py`) each\n294\tre-pump every streamed chunk through their own anyio memory-object-stream, so\n295\tcost scaled with `chunk_count x middleware_layers` and dominated wall-clock\n296\ttime at the 100k-row cap — not CSV encoding or DB query time, which were both\n297\tsub-second in isolation. Three within-design fixes closed the gap (see\n298\t`.pipeline/debug-notes.md` for the full isolation profiling):\n299\t- `src/services/usage_export_service.py` batches `_ROWS_PER_CHUNK = 1000`\n300\t  encoded rows per yielded chunk (was one row per chunk) — the primary lever,\n301\t  cutting chunk count ~1,000x at the cap while staying constant-memory (the\n302\t  buffer holds at most one batch).\n303\t- `src/api/csv_export.py`'s `escape_csv_text_cell` replaced its per-character\n304\t  strip loop with a precompiled `str.translate` deletion table (semantics\n305\t  verified identical across all C0/DEL codepoints).\n306\t- `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`'s `stream_usage_rollups` tunes the\n307\t  server-side cursor with `execution_options(yield_per=_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH)`\n308\t  (`_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH = 5000`) — more rows fetched per DB round-trip,\n309\t  cursor still never abandoned.\n310\t\n311\tNet effect: p95 dropped from ~10.7s to a stable **p95 ~1.6-2.1s** (10-sample\n312\tmeasurement). The original 500ms target proved unreachable within the\n313\tapproved constant-memory-streaming design (an irreducible ~0.85-1.0s floor\n314\tfrom the server-side cursor drain + per-row CSV encoding, even discounting\n315\tmiddleware). The human confirmed a revised, binding budget of **p95 <=\n316\t3,000ms at the 100,000-row cap** at the 2026-07-09 escalation, which\n317\t`tests/integration/test_usage_export_perf.py` now hard-asserts (AC16); this\n318\tsession's re-run measured p95 1,643.87ms, comfortably under the bound.\n319\t"}]},"uuid":"10fa1823-502f-4423-acf6-36a9dcec7214","timestamp":"2026-07-11T23:31:22.713Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/mnt/c/Users/brett/OneDrive/Documents/GitHub/meterly-pipeline-test/docs/system_architecture.md","content":"# Meterly — system architecture\n\n## Overview\n\nMeterly ingests metered usage events, serves aggregated per-customer/metric\ncounters (single-bucket read or a streamed CSV export), and enforces\nadmin-set per-customer, per-metric usage caps (\"quotas\"), which an admin key\ncan also list and remove. Six authenticated HTTP endpoints, one PostgreSQL\ndatabase, one Redis rate-limit store, running as a Docker container on ECS\nFargate behind an ALB.\n\n```\nClient --HTTPS+API key--> ALB --> FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\n                                     |-- Tier-1 (IP) / Tier-2 (api_key_id) throttle --> Redis\n                                     |-- bound-parameter SQL, RLS-scoped -------------> RDS PostgreSQL\n                                     |-- DB credential fetch ------------------------> Secrets Manager\n                                     |-- traces/logs/errors -------------------------> CloudWatch/X-Ray/Sentry\n```\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n    Client[Client] -->|\"HTTPS + API key\"| ALB[ALB]\n    ALB --> FastAPI[\"FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\"]\n    FastAPI -->|\"Tier-1 IP+route / Tier-2 api_key_id throttle\"| Redis[(Redis)]\n    FastAPI -->|\"require_api_key: cache hit or Argon2id verify\"| AuthDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: api_keys)]\n    FastAPI -->|\"POST /v1/events: insert + quota check + rollup upsert\"| EventsDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: events / usage_rollup / quotas)]\n    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/usage: read rollup\"| EventsDB\n    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/usage/export: pre-flight COUNT + streamed SELECT\"| EventsDB\n    FastAPI -->|\"PUT /v1/quotas: upsert cap\"| EventsDB\n    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/quotas: list caller's caps\"| EventsDB\n    FastAPI -->|\"DELETE /v1/quotas: remove one cap\"| EventsDB\n    FastAPI -->|\"DB credential fetch\"| Secrets[Secrets Manager]\n    FastAPI -->|\"traces/logs/errors\"| Observability[\"CloudWatch / X-Ray / Sentry\"]\n```\n\n## Request flow — `POST /v1/events`\n\n1. Request-id/trace assigned, security headers queued (`src/logging/middleware.py`, `src/api/middleware.py`).\n2. Tier-1 IP+route throttle (Redis token bucket; fails open on a Redis outage).\n3. `require_api_key` — split-token parse, in-process verification-cache check,\n   falling back to a DB lookup + Argon2id verify on a cache miss\n   (`src/auth/__init__.py`, `src/auth/api_key.py`).\n4. Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`).\n5. Pydantic schema validation (`src/api/schemas/events.py`) — anchored\n   allowlists, `extra='forbid'`.\n6. `events_service.create_event` — one transaction:\n   `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING`, and only\n   if a row was inserted:\n   - the quota check: `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` locks the caller's\n     quota row for `(customer, metric)` (if one exists) and reads the\n     current-window rollup total fresh; if `R + Q > L` the service raises\n     `QuotaExceededError` (429 `quota_exceeded`, `Retry-After` to the next\n     hour boundary), which propagates out of the transaction and rolls back\n     the event insert — no partial write, no rollup increment\n     (`src/services/events_service.py`, `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n   - otherwise, `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO UPDATE` the `usage_rollup`\n     counter (`src/repositories/events_repo.py`).\n   A duplicate `idempotency_key` (replay) never reaches the quota check at\n   all — only the winning-insert branch does.\n7. Error-envelope boundary catches anything unhandled and returns the generic\n   `{error:{code,message,requestId}}` shape (`src/api/errors.py`); `AppError`\n   lets a handler attach an explicit `app_code` (e.g. `quota_exceeded`) that\n   overrides the default status->code map, so two different 429s\n   (`rate_limited` vs. `quota_exceeded`) stay distinguishable to the caller.\n\n## Request flow — `GET /v1/usage`\n\nSame auth/throttle/error stack; the service floors `window` to the UTC hour\nand reads a single `usage_rollup` row scoped by the caller's `api_key_id`\n(`src/services/usage_service.py`, `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`). A missing\nbucket returns zeros with 200, never 404.\n\n## Request flow — `GET /v1/usage/export`\n\nSame auth/throttle/error stack, plus a two-phase pre-flight-then-stream\ndesign (`src/api/routes/usage_export.py`,\n`src/services/usage_export_service.py`,\n`src/repositories/usage_repo.py`):\n\n1. `UsageExportQueryParams` validates the optional `customer_id`/`metric`/\n   `from`/`to` filters (`src/api/schemas/usage_export.py`) — reuses the same\n   `CustomerId`/`Metric` anchored allowlists as `events.py` and the same\n   `[now-90d, now+1h]` bound idiom as `usage.py`'s `window`, applied here to\n   a `[from, to]` range.\n2. **Pre-flight cap check** (`prepare_export`): a `COUNT(*)` over the\n   caller's rows (scoped by `api_key_id` first, plus the optional filters)\n   inside its own transaction. Over 100,000 rows -> 422\n   `validation_failed`, logged at `warn` (`usage.export.rejected`). This\n   runs, and fully resolves, *before* any response byte — once a\n   `StreamingResponse` is constructed the status line is already 200 and the\n   cap decision can no longer cleanly 422. Any *other* (non-cap) error here\n   propagates uncaught to the error-envelope boundary: a fail-closed generic\n   500, transaction rolled back, no stream ever started.\n3. **Stream** (`stream_export_csv`): a `StreamingResponse` whose body\n   generator is pulled by Starlette only after the handler returns, so it\n   opens its **own** tenant-scoped transaction (the `SET LOCAL\n   app.current_api_key_id` RLS-backstop setting and the server-side cursor\n   both need to stay valid for the whole stream, not just the pre-flight\n   phase). Yields the header row first, always (an empty result is a 200\n   header-only CSV, never 404), then one CSV-encoded row per record from\n   `stream_usage_rollups` (`ORDER BY window_start, customer_id, metric` — a\n   fixed literal, never client-derived — `LIMIT 100000`), each row written\n   into a reused `io.StringIO` via stdlib `csv.writer` (RFC 4180, CRLF,\n   `QUOTE_MINIMAL`) and drained to bytes immediately — constant memory\n   throughout. `customer_id`/`metric` text cells pass through\n   `src/api/csv_export.py`'s `escape_csv_text_cell` (the OWASP\n   formula-injection defense: a leading `= + - @ \\t \\r` gets a `'` prefix)\n   *before* reaching the writer; numeric/timestamp cells are formatted but\n   never escaped (they're server-generated, never attacker-controlled).\n   Logs exactly one `usage.export` audit event in a `finally` block\n   (`rowCount`, `capped`, `completed`, filter-presence booleans — never the\n   raw `customer_id`/`metric` values), so a client disconnect or a mid-stream\n   DB error still records what was actually sent.\n\nResponse headers: `Content-Type: text/csv; charset=utf-8`,\n`Content-Disposition: attachment; filename=\"usage-export-<UTC\ntimestamp>.csv\"` (no tenant identifier in the filename), plus the inherited\n`nosniff` and (via the existing `/v1/usage`-prefix rule in\n`src/api/middleware.py`) `Cache-Control: no-store`.\n\n**Accepted risk — mid-stream failure truncates the CSV.** Once the 200\nstatus line and header bytes are on the wire, an unhandled error partway\nthrough the stream can no longer be converted to a clean error envelope; the\nclient sees a truncated download it can re-request. This is strictly the\n*post-200* case — the pre-flight `COUNT` phase above is fully recoverable\nand does return the generic 500 envelope. Bounded by the row cap + Tier-2\nthrottle + connection-pool sizing; batched keyset pagination is the future\nmitigation if this needs closing further.\n\n## Request flow — `PUT /v1/quotas`\n\nAdmin-scoped create-or-replace of a per-customer, per-metric usage cap.\nAuth -> Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle -> an `admin`-scope assertion in the\nroute's composed dependency (403 `forbidden` for a non-admin key) -> schema\nvalidation (`src/api/schemas/quotas.py`) -> `upsert_tenant_quota`, a single\n`INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ...\nRETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted` that reports create-vs-replace in one\nround-trip (201 create / 200 replace), with a `quota.upsert` audit log\n(`src/api/routes/quotas.py`, `src/services/quota_service.py`,\n`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`).\n\n## Request flow — `GET /v1/quotas` and `DELETE /v1/quotas`\n\nBoth reuse the same `_require_admin_and_throttled` dependency chain as `PUT`\n(auth -> Tier-2 per-`api_key_id` throttle -> `admin`-scope assertion, 403\n`forbidden` for a non-admin key) — no new auth path or scope\n(`src/api/routes/quotas.py`).\n\n- **`GET /v1/quotas`** (`list_quotas_endpoint` -> `quota_service.list_tenant_quotas`\n  -> `quotas_repo.list_quotas`) takes no request parameter and returns the\n  caller's **full, unpaginated** quota list as `list[QuotaResponse]`\n  (`{customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}` only), via an `api_key_id`-scoped\n  `SELECT ... ORDER BY customer_id, metric` (index-friendly on the table's PK\n  prefix, so the sort is effectively free). An empty tenant gets `200 []`,\n  never 404. Deliberately not given a dedicated business-audit log (a plain\n  read of the caller's own config, mirroring `GET /v1/usage`).\n- **`DELETE /v1/quotas?customer_id=X&metric=Y`** (`delete_quota_endpoint` ->\n  `quota_service.delete_tenant_quota` -> `quotas_repo.delete_quota`) validates\n  the two query params through `QuotaDeleteParams` (the same anchored\n  `CustomerId`/`Metric` allowlists `PUT` uses, `extra='forbid'`), then issues a\n  single parameterized `DELETE ... WHERE api_key_id = :api_key_id AND\n  customer_id = :customer_id AND metric = :metric RETURNING customer_id`. A\n  matched row -> **204 No Content**; no matched row -> **404** `not_found`\n  (explicit, not silently idempotent) — a cross-tenant delete attempt is\n  indistinguishable from this outcome, since the `api_key_id` filter plus the\n  `quotas_tenant_isolation` **FORCE** RLS backstop (migration `0003`) mean the\n  query can never see another tenant's row to remove it. On success, logs one\n  `quota.delete` INFO event (`userId`, `action=\"delete\"`, `customer_id`\n  [facade-redacted], `metric`, `requestId`) — the audit trail for who removed\n  which cap.\n- **No `usage_rollup` side effect:** `delete_quota` issues **only** a `DELETE`\n  on `quotas`; it never touches `usage_rollup`. A DELETE racing an in-flight\n  `POST /v1/events` for the same `(customer, metric)` serializes on the shared\n  quota-row lock (the DELETE's implicit row lock vs. the ingest's `SELECT ...\n  FOR UPDATE OF q`) — whichever commits first determines the outcome for\n  everything that reads after; no additional synchronization is added (the\n  same replacement-race semantics `PUT` already has).\n- **Safe-error / fail-closed:** an unexpected exception on either path (e.g. a\n  DB driver/connection error) propagates to the existing\n  `handle_unexpected_error` catch-all (`src/api/errors.py`) -> generic `{code:\n  internal}` 500 (no stack/SQL/type/path leak). Because both service functions\n  run inside `scoped_transaction`, the exception also rolls the transaction\n  back — `DELETE` leaves the target row intact (no partial delete); `GET` is\n  read-only, so there is nothing to unwind. Same boundary and guarantee as\n  `POST /v1/events`'s precedent.\n- **CORS:** `DELETE` was added to `configure_cors`'s `allow_methods`\n  (`src/api/middleware.py`) for completeness — the origin allowlist is empty\n  in this server-to-server API, so the change is not a live control.\n\n## Data model\n\n- `api_keys` — the tenant/credential table (migration 0001), extended with a\n  `scope` column (migration 0003: `'ingest'` default, `'admin'` elevated).\n  `secret_hash` is Argon2id; `key_id` is the public split-token lookup\n  handle. `scope='admin'` is a superset scope — an admin key does everything\n  an ingest key does, plus call `PUT`/`GET`/`DELETE /v1/quotas`; a tenant that\n  wants quotas provisions one admin-scoped key and uses it for all three.\n- `events` — append-only ingest log (migration 0001). `UNIQUE (api_key_id,\n  idempotency_key)` is the idempotency guarantee; RLS policy\n  `events_tenant_isolation` is the application-scoping backstop.\n- `usage_rollup` — derived hourly aggregate (migration 0002, expand +\n  backfill from `events`). Composite PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric,\n  window_start)`; RLS policy `usage_rollup_tenant_isolation`.\n- `quotas` — per-tenant, per-customer, per-metric usage caps (migration\n  0003). PK `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)`; `CHECK (limit_per_window >=\n  1)`; RLS policy `quotas_tenant_isolation`. The `POST /v1/events` quota\n  check takes `FOR UPDATE` on this row to serialize concurrent writers for\n  the same `(customer, metric)` — see *Quota enforcement / atomicity* below.\n\n## Quota enforcement / atomicity\n\nStrict enforcement (\"usage can never exceed `L`\") is a check-then-act on a\nshared counter — the classic TOCTOU. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked`\n(`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`) makes it race-free with a `SELECT\nlimit_per_window ... FOR UPDATE` on the quota row, run **as a separate\nstatement from the subsequent `usage_rollup` read**, both inside the same\ntransaction as the event insert and rollup increment\n(`src/services/events_service.py`).\n\nThis two-round-trip shape is deliberate, not incidental: PostgreSQL's `FOR\nUPDATE` only guarantees a fresh re-check of the *locked* row itself when a\nwaiter unblocks after the lock holder commits — it does **not** force a\nfresh snapshot for another table read in the same statement (e.g. a `LEFT\nJOIN` to `usage_rollup`). A waiter queued before the holder committed would\nevaluate that join against its own pre-wait snapshot and read a stale total,\nsilently letting concurrent writers jointly exceed the cap. Splitting the\nlock-acquire and the rollup-read into two statements gives the second query\nits own fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot (taken *after* the lock is held),\nwhich does reflect everything the previous holder just committed. This was\nverified empirically during implementation: a single combined\n`LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` statement let every concurrent waiter read\nthe same stale total and all get admitted; the two-statement version\ncorrectly serializes and caps admission at `L`\n(`tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py`).\n\nUnlimited customers (no quota row) take no lock at all — the first `SELECT\n... FOR UPDATE` simply matches zero rows, so the common, zero-contention\npath stays cheap (AC20 measures its added latency under load).\n\n## Auth\n\nSplit-token API keys (`mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>`), Argon2id-hashed at rest.\nClients present the key in the standard bearer scheme —\n`Authorization: Bearer mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` — which is also the auth\ncontext a DAST job (ZAP/Schemathesis) reads to authenticate its scan (DAST-3).\nAn in-process, TTL-bounded verification cache (keyed on the public `key_id`,\nguarded by a constant-time digest comparison) avoids paying the Argon2id cost\non every request while the durable store stays Argon2id-only. See\n`src/auth/__init__.py` for the full tradeoff writeup and\n`scripts/seed_api_key.py` for the only key-provisioning path (no HTTP\nendpoint in this build's scope; pass `--admin` to provision a `scope='admin'`\nkey for `PUT`/`GET`/`DELETE /v1/quotas`, including the DAST-context admin test\nkey, DAST-3).\n\n## Rate limiting\n\nTwo Redis token-bucket tiers (`src/auth/rate_limit.py`): Tier-1 pre-auth,\nkeyed on IP+route; Tier-2 post-auth, keyed on the authenticated\n`api_key_id`. Both fail open (log a warning, allow the request) on a Redis\nconnection error rather than failing every request — an availability\ntradeoff recorded in `.pipeline/surface-delta.md`.\n\n## Observability\n\nStructured JSON logs (structlog) to stdout -> CloudWatch, with a centralized\nredaction processor (`src/logging/__init__.py`). OTel traces -> ADOT sidecar\n-> X-Ray; Sentry for release-tagged error tracking with a `before_send`\nPII/secret scrubber (`src/observability/`). SLO burn-rate alarms and the\nminimum-three canary alarms are declared in `infra/modules/observability`.\n\n## Infrastructure\n\nTerraform under `infra/`: `modules/{network,compute,data,observability,edge}`\nhold the real resources; `envs/{staging,prod}/main.tf` are the two\nself-contained deploy roots (own provider + backend, since Terraform only\npermits a backend configuration in a root module) that instantiate the same\nmodules at different scale. See each module's file header comments for the\nspecific resources and the security-baseline items they satisfy\n(encryption at rest, private subnets, least-privilege IAM, no `BYPASSRLS`).\n\n## Known deviations / accepted risks\n\nSee `.pipeline/surface-delta.md` for the rate-limit fail-open behavior and the\nOTel/Sentry wiring-at-construction-time change vs. the plan's original\nlifespan-hook placement. See `plan.md`'s \"Open questions\" section for the\naccepted risks around key-revocation latency, `api_key_id`-as-tenant-scope,\nand the Postgres app-role bootstrap's CI-network-reachability prerequisite.\n\n**`GET /v1/usage/export` p95 at the 100,000-row cap — resolved (was: plan\n§\"Open questions\" #1, originally unconfirmed).** The first measured p95\n(~10.7s locally / 25.2s on testing's independent re-measure) was root-caused\nduring debugging to the streaming generator yielding **one chunk per row**:\nthe app's four nested `BaseHTTPMiddleware` layers (`src/main.py`) each\nre-pump every streamed chunk through their own anyio memory-object-stream, so\ncost scaled with `chunk_count x middleware_layers` and dominated wall-clock\ntime at the 100k-row cap — not CSV encoding or DB query time, which were both\nsub-second in isolation. Three within-design fixes closed the gap (see\n`.pipeline/debug-notes.md` for the full isolation profiling):\n- `src/services/usage_export_service.py` batches `_ROWS_PER_CHUNK = 1000`\n  encoded rows per yielded chunk (was one row per chunk) — the primary lever,\n  cutting chunk count ~1,000x at the cap while staying constant-memory (the\n  buffer holds at most one batch).\n- `src/api/csv_export.py`'s `escape_csv_text_cell` replaced its per-character\n  strip loop with a precompiled `str.translate` deletion table (semantics\n  verified identical across all C0/DEL codepoints).\n- `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`'s `stream_usage_rollups` tunes the\n  server-side cursor with `execution_options(yield_per=_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH)`\n  (`_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH = 5000`) — more rows fetched per DB round-trip,\n  cursor still never abandoned.\n\nNet effect: p95 dropped from ~10.7s to a stable **p95 ~1.6-2.1s** (10-sample\nmeasurement). The original 500ms target proved unreachable within the\napproved constant-memory-streaming design (an irreducible ~0.85-1.0s floor\nfrom the server-side cursor drain + per-row CSV encoding, even discounting\nmiddleware). The human confirmed a revised, binding budget of **p95 <=\n3,000ms at the 100,000-row cap** at the 2026-07-09 escalation, which\n`tests/integration/test_usage_export_perf.py` now hard-asserts (AC16); this\nsession's re-run measured p95 1,643.87ms, comfortably under the bound.\n","numLines":319,"startLine":1,"totalLines":319}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"65554e78-8fd3-4ce4-aa8a-1ae3f02406c4","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/mnt/c/Users/brett/OneDrive/Documents/GitHub/meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"8b12bd3f-3c00-43c5-ad29-92ed49e714d3","version":"2.1.207","gitBranch":"feature/usage-daily"}
